explanation:
The MISRA requirement concerns for-loops and states that the behaviour of any functions called within a loop is considered part of the loop body. To determine whether any for-loop (either in OS_cp itself or in any function it calls while inside a loop) violates the rule, the following additional symbols are required:

- OS_read: Called directly inside the outer while loop. Its implementation must be inspected for any for-loops (and to see whether those for-loops violate the rule or modify objects used by enclosing loops).
- OS_TimedRead: OS_read may call OS_TimedRead. Any for-loops in OS_TimedRead form part of the loop behaviour and must be checked.
- OS_write: Called inside the inner write loop. Its implementation may contain for-loops or side effects relevant to the for-loop rule.
- OS_TimedWrite: OS_write may call OS_TimedWrite; its for-loops (if any) must be checked as part of the loop behaviour.

(The following are UT/unit-test stub helpers that appear as callees of the above read/write paths in the static call graph:) 
- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType
- UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData
- UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr
- UT_GetStubEntry
- UT_ClearStubEntry
- UT_DefaultStubImpl
- UT_SetHandlerFunction
- UtAssert_Abort
- UtAssert_GetContext

Reason: the UT stub/harness functions may be invoked (directly or indirectly) by OS_read/OS_write (per the static call graph). Any for-loops present in these helper/stub implementations are considered part of the behaviour of the loop in OS_cp (per the MISRA wording). Therefore their implementations must be examined to conclude whether any for-loop in the overall execution path is well-formed under the rule. These symbols are the minimal set required to trace and inspect all functions invoked from the loop bodies of OS_cp for potential for-loops and related side-effects.
